Indonesia Stocks: Jaya Konstruksi Manggala, Salim Ivomas, Timah

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 
2011-06-09T09:41:33Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-09/indonesia-stocks-jaya-konstruksi-manggala-salim-ivomas-timah.html
Shares of the following companies had
unusual moves in Indonesian trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are as of the 4 p.m. Jakarta-time close.  The  Jakarta Composite index (JCI)  dropped 19.63 points, or 0.5
percent, to 3,806.19, falling for a second day.  PT Jaya Konstruksi Manggala Pratama (JKON IJ), an
Indonesian builder, gained 7.4 percent to 870 rupiah, the
highest close since May 27. The company said it will pay a
dividend of 13 rupiah a share, amounting to 33 percent of last
year’s net income.  PT Medco Energi Internasional (MEDC IJ), Indonesia’s
largest listed oil company, dropped 2.9 percent to 2,475 rupiah,
the lowest level since March 1, 2010. PT Perusahaan Listrik
Negara decided to take over a power-plant project from a group
of investors led by a Medco unit, the detik.com news website
reported, citing Murtaqi Syamsuddin, a director at Listrik
Negara. Syamsuddin didn’t reply to a text message seeking
confirmation. Medco hasn’t received any formal notification of a
plan, Corporate Secretary Cisca Alimin said by phone.  PT Salim Ivomas Pratama (SIMP IJ), a producer of cooking
oil, margarine and shortening, rose 14 percent to 1,250 rupiah
on its trading debut. The company raised 3.48 trillion rupiah
($408 million) in an initial public offering last month to repay
debt and fund expansions.  PT Timah (TINS IJ),  Indonesia ’s biggest tin producer, fell
1.9 percent to 2,550 rupiah, the lowest close since March 22.
Tin futures declined for a sixth straight day yesterday to the
lowest settlement price since Dec. 8.  To contact the reporter on this story:
